{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b5bb6303e256120c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tFlow Matching-Based Speech Source Separation with Best-of-N Biometric\n2\tSampling\n3\t\n4\tAnastasia Zorkina 1 Alexandr Anikin 1 Nikita Khmelev 1 2 Anastasiya Korenevskaya 1 Sergey Novoselov 1 2\n5\tVladimir Volokhov 1 2 Maxim Korenevsky 2 Yuriy Matveev 1\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.06088v1 [cs.SD] 7 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\tAbstract\n10\t\n11\tModern deterministic speech source separation systems\n12\tbased on Transformer and Conformer architectures achieve\n13\tSI-SDRi above 24 dB on the WSJ0-2mix benchmark (Zhao\n14\tet al., 2024; Shin et al., 2024). Generative counterparts,\n15\tincluding hybrid schemes (Lutati et al., 2024; Wang et al.,\n16\t2024) and fully generative diffusion or flow matching models (Scheibler et al., 2023; Dong et al., 2025; Scheibler et al.,\n17\t2025), offer new modeling paradigms that improve perceptual naturalness at the cost of sampling variance and higher\n18\tcomputation.\n19\t\n20\tSingle-channel speech separation remains challenging for real-world deployment due to source\n21\tpermutation ambiguity, sampling variability of\n22\tgenerative models, and the difficulty of processing long recordings with chunk-wise inference.\n23\tWe address these issues with a conditional flowmatching-based method that produces an ordered\n24\ttwo-source output conditioned on the mixture. A\n25\tfrozen speaker encoder defines the source order\n26\tduring training and is reused at inference for biometric best-of-N candidate selection and chunklevel channel alignment. We evaluate separation\n27\tquality on Libri2Mix benchmark using SI-SDR,\n28\tPESQ, and ESTOI, and measure downstream impact using cpWER for automatic speech recognition and EER for speaker verification. The results\n29\tshow that the proposed Transformer U-Net variant\n30\tis competitive with strong baselines in objective\n31\tseparation metrics and achieves the lowest downstream automatic speech recognition and speaker\n32\tverification error rates in all evaluated settings.\n33\t\n34\tDeploying these systems in practice faces additional hurdles:\n35\tnon-causality, processing of long recordings, downstream\n36\tintegration, and computational efficiency. In this work, we\n37\tpropose a practical speech separation system based on conditional flow matching, built on generative speech enhancement models from the NVIDIA NeMo Toolkit (Jukić et al.,\n38\t2024; Ku et al., 2025). We formulate two-speaker separation as a conditional generation of a structured waveform\n39\tthat contains both separated sources. Besides, we introduce a best-of-N biometric sampling procedure that selects\n40\tthe most speaker-disentangled generation among multiple\n41\tstochastic candidates.\n42\tThe main contributions of this work are as follows: 1) A\n43\tflow-matching-based speech separation method adapted\n44\tfrom generative speech enhancement. 2) A best-of-N\n45\tbiometric criterion for inference-time candidate selection.\n46\t3) Long-form processing via chunk-wise generation combined with speaker-recognition-based channel tracking. 4)\n47\tEvaluation of downstream ASR and SR performance after\n48\tuse of our speech source separation system.\n49\t\n50\t1. Introduction\n51\tSpeech source separation, also known as the “cocktail party\n52\tproblem”, is a fundamental task in audio processing and\n53\tspeech technologies (Li et al., 2025; Araki et al., 2025; Wang\n54\t& Luo, 2025). It aims to extract individual speech signals\n55\tfrom a mixture, benefiting systems such as automatic speech\n56\trecognition (ASR), speaker recognition (SR), intelligent\n57\tvoice assistants, and others. Despite rapid progress driven\n58\tby deep learning, speech separation remains challenging\n59\tdue to acoustic complexity, the ill-posed nature of singlechannel inversion, varying overlap patterns, permutation\n60\tambiguity, and high speaker variability.\n61\t\n62\t2. Background\n63\tSpeech source separation. Formally, the task isPto recover K signals s1 , . . . , sK from a mixture m = k sk .\n64\tPermutation-invariant training (PIT) (Yu et al., 2017; Kolbæk et al., 2017) resolves source-ordering symmetry at the\n65\tloss level but leaves output channels interchangeable at inference, complicating block-wise processing of long-form\n66\taudio. An information-theoretic upper bound of 23.1 dB SISDRi has been established for deterministic separators (Lu-\n67\t\n68\t1\n69\t\n70\tITMO University, Speech Processing Group, Russia 2 Speech\n71\tTechnology Center Ltd., R&D department, Russia. Correspondence to: Anastasia Zorkina <zorkina@speechpro.com>.\n72\t\n73\t1\n74\t\n75\t\fFlow Matching-Based Speech Source Separation with Best-of-N Biometric Sampling\n76\t\n77\ttati et al., 2022); under heavy overlap, they also introduce\n78\tperceptual artefacts that SI-SDR does not capture but that\n79\tdownstream ASR/SR penalise (Wang & Luo, 2025). Generative separators sidestep both issues by sampling from\n80\tp(s1 , . . . , sK | m) via diffusion or conditional flow matching (Lipman et al., 2022), at the price of run-to-run sampling\n81\tvariance for which no principled inference-time selection\n82\tcriterion has been proposed.\n83\tSpeaker recognition. Speaker recognition is the task of\n84\tidentifying a speaker from an audio recording. Its canonical formulation is speaker verification (SV): determining\n85\twhether two recordings originate from the same speaker.\n86\tState-of-the-art systems are based on deep neural networks,\n87\teither trained from scratch for this task (e.g., ECAPATDNN (Desplanques et al., 2020), ReDimNet (Yakovlev\n88\tet al., 2024)) or adapted from speech foundation models\n89\t(e.g., Wav2Vec 2.0-TDNN (Novoselov et al., 2022)). Training is performed as a speaker classification problem (7,205\n90\tclasses on VoxCeleb 1 & 2 (Nagrani et al., 2017)), employing feature normalization and an additive angular margin\n91\tin the softmax objective (AAM-Softmax) to enhance class\n92\tseparability. At inference time, the classification layer is\n93\tdiscarded, and the model extracts a compact speaker embedding; embeddings from different recordings are then\n94\tcompared via cosine similarity.\n95\t\n96\tFigure 1. Training procedure of the proposed conditional flow\n97\tmatching demixer.\n98\t\n99\tintermediate state xt sampled from this path, the estimator\n100\tis trained with\n101\th\n102\ti\n103\t2\n104\tLCFM (θ) = E ∥vt (xt , c; θ) − ut (xt | x0 , x1 )∥2 . (2)\n105\tWe formulate two-speaker speech separation as a conditional generation, guided by some feature c. The observed\n106\tmixture waveform is m = s1 + s2 , where s1 and s2 are\n107\tspeech signals from two speakers. For each mixture, c is\n108\tobtained from the complex STFT features of the mixturederived signal, while x1 denotes the complex STFT features of the corresponding separated-source signal; therefore, both predicted and target velocities are defined in the\n109\tsame STFT feature space.\n110\t\n111\tBest-of-N sampling. Best-of-N returns the highestranked of N independent generator samples under an external verifier, trading inference compute for quality without\n112\tretraining the generator. It underpins LLM alignment (Stiennon et al., 2020), verifier-based mathematical reasoning\n113\t(Cobbe et al., 2021), code generation (Chen et al., 2021),\n114\tand inference-time scaling of text-to-image diffusion (Xie\n115\tet al., 2025; Choi et al., 2025).\n116\t\n117\t3.2. Training Procedure\n118\t\n119\tIn conditional generation, we approximate this vector field\n120\twith a neural estimator vt (xt , c; θ), where xt is the current\n121\tstate, c is the conditioning information, and θ are trainable\n122\tparameters.\n123\t\n124\tThe training pipeline is shown in Fig. 1. Each training\n125\texample consists of a mixture m and two clean sources\n126\t(s1 , s2 ); however, these references do not by themselves\n127\tdefine a canonical target order. Single-channel separation\n128\tis ill-posed and permutation ambiguous: the source order\n129\tand its swapped version define the same mixture, while the\n130\tmodel must learn a deterministic output order. To make\n131\tthe target closer to well-defined, we resolve this ambiguity\n132\tusing biometric comparison with a pretrained speaker encoder η: source embeddings are compared with a predefined\n133\treference speaker embedding eref using cosine similarity,\n134\tyielding an ordered pair (sA , sB ), where sA is the source\n135\tcloser to eref . We concatenate the ordered sources through\n136\ta fixed non-speech separator, x̄ = sA ∥r∥sB , and duplicate\n137\tthe mixture in the same layout, m̄ = m∥r∥m; their complex STFT features define x1 and c, respectively. Thus, the\n138\tsource separation task is reduced to a denoising task, where\n139\tthe structural interference of the reversely oriented speech\n140\tsignal sB ∥r∥sA should be removed from m̄.\n141\t\n142\tTo obtain a tractable training target, we follow the optimaltransport conditional path (Lipman et al., 2022). Given\n143\tx1 ∼ pdata (· | c), x0 ∼ N (0, I), t ∼ U[0, 1], and an\n144\t\n145\tDuring training, we sample x0 ∼ N (0, I) and t ∼ U(0, 1),\n146\tthen form xt using the conditional path above. The neural\n147\testimator receives xt , the conditioning representation c, and\n148\t\n149\t3. Proposed Method\n150\t3.1. Conditional Flow Matching Formulation\n151\tFlow matching defines generation through a time-dependent\n152\tvector field whose flow map transports samples from a simple prior distribution to the data distribution. Let ϕt denote\n153\tthe flow map induced by a vector field ut ,\n154\td\n155\tϕt (x) = ut (ϕt (x)),\n156\tdt\n157\t\n158\tϕ0 (x) = x.\n159\t\n160\t(1)\n161\t\n162\t2\n163\t\n164\t\fFlow Matching-Based Speech Source Separation with Best-of-N Biometric Sampling\n165\t\n166\t4. Experimental Setup\n167\t\n168\tthe time t, and is optimized with the conditional flow matching loss. Conditional dropout is applied by replacing c with\n169\tzeros with probability 1 − pcond , exposing the estimator to\n170\tboth conditional and unconditional inputs.\n171\t\n172\t4.1. Data and Preprocessing\n173\tWe use the two-speaker Libri2Mix benchmark from the\n174\tLibriMix corpus (Cosentino et al., 2020): 16 kHz max,\n175\ttrain-360 for training, and the corresponding test subsets\n176\tfor evaluation. Experiments are reported for the official\n177\tmix clean and mix both mixture types.\n178\t\n179\t3.3. Inference Pipeline\n180\tConventional source separation systems typically operate on\n181\ta complete input segment, which limits their applicability to\n182\tlong-form recordings. Our inference pipeline instead targets\n183\trecordings of arbitrary duration by processing the mixture\n184\tchunk by chunk. This requires two stages: local generation\n185\tfor each chunk and subsequent alignment of chunk-level\n186\toutputs.\n187\t\n188\tWe additionally apply online augmentation. We load 2second synchronized mixture/source segments, reverberate\n189\tboth sources with independently selected speaker RIRs, mix\n190\tthem with target-to-interferer SNR sampled from [0, 5] dB,\n191\tand add WHAM! (Wichern et al., 2019), MUSAN (Snyder\n192\tet al., 2015), or CHiME-8 (Cornell et al., 2024) noise to the\n193\tmixture with SNR sampled from [10, 20] dB. Targets are the\n194\treverberated clean sources. We keep the central 1-second\n195\tregion after augmentation to suppress convolution boundary\n196\tartifacts.\n197\t\n198\tChunk-level generation. Given a mixture recording m,\n199\twe split it into 1-second chunks with a 0.5-second hop.\n200\tEach chunk mc is processed independently using the same\n201\trepresentation as in training: the mixture-derived condition\n202\tis encoded into complex STFT features, the initial state is\n203\tsampled as Gaussian noise x0 ∼ N (0, I), and the learned\n204\tODE is solved with an Euler sampler to produce a local\n205\tsource pair (ŝc,A , ŝc,B ).\n206\t\n207\tTargets are represented as sA ∥r∥sB and conditions as\n208\tm∥r∥m, where r is a 1000-sample constant separator with\n209\tamplitude 0.5 (62.5 ms at 16 kHz). Following the NVIDIA\n210\tNeMo Toolkit implementation (Kuchaiev et al., 2019), we\n211\tuse complex STFT features with hop length 128, magnitude\n212\tpower 0.5, and scale factor 0.33. The FFT length is 254\n213\tfor NCSN++ (ConvUnet) and 510 for Transformer U-Net\n214\t(TUnet).\n215\t\n216\tThe stochasticity of flow-based generation allows us to draw\n217\tmultiple plausible separations for the same chunk. We exploit this at inference time through best-of-N biometric\n218\tsampling: from N independently generated candidates, we\n219\tselect the pair whose output-channel speaker embeddings\n220\tare least similar,\n221\t\u0010\n222\t\u0011\n223\t(i)\n224\t(i)\n225\ti∗ = arg min cos η(ŝc,A ), η(ŝc,B ) .\n226\ti\n227\t\n228\t4.2. Models and Baselines\n229\tWe evaluate two velocity estimators: an NCSN++ spectrogram network (Song et al., 2021), referred to as ConvUnet in\n230\tthe results, and a 24-layer Spectrogram Transformer U-Net\n231\t(TUnet) initialized from the NVIDIA generative speech\n232\trestoration checkpoint (Ku et al., 2025). Source ordering, best-of-N selection, and chunk alignment use a frozen\n233\tWav2Vec 2.0-based speaker embedding model (Novoselov\n234\tet al., 2022).\n235\t\n236\t(3)\n237\t\n238\tThis favors candidates in which the two generated channels\n239\tcorrespond to different speakers.\n240\tChunk alignment. After chunk-level generation, the local\n241\tchannel order must be made consistent before reconstruction, since the two generated sources may swap between\n242\tadjacent chunks. We use biometric alignment based on the\n243\tspeaker embeddings of the generated channels. For each\n244\tglobal output channel, embeddings from accepted chunks\n245\tare accumulated and clustered into two centroids, which\n246\tgives a more robust channel representation in the presence\n247\tof noise, leakage, or locally unreliable generations. A new\n248\tchunk is assigned to the channel order whose embeddings\n249\tbest match the current centroids; otherwise, its two channels\n250\tare swapped. For controlled analysis, we also report an\n251\toracle SI-SDR alignment, which chooses the chunk permutation using ground-truth sources and serves as a reference\n252\talignment upper bound. Finally, the aligned chunks are\n253\tplaced back at their original time positions and combined by\n254\toverlap-add averaging, yielding two full-length separated\n255\twaveforms.\n256\t\n257\tTraining uses Adam optimizer, learning rate 10−4 with cosine decay to 10−6 , gradient clipping, and EMA decay\n258\t0.999. NCSN++ is trained for up to 300 epochs on NVIDIA\n259\tA100 GPUs; Transformer U-Net is trained for up to 150\n260\tepochs on one A100. We use conditional dropout with\n261\tpcond = 0.99.\n262\tBaselines are DiffSep (Scheibler et al., 2023), and SepReformer (Shin et al., 2024) (Large model evaluated in both\n263\tfull-utterance and chunked modes). Additionally recent target speaker extraction method MeanFlow-TSE (Shimizu\n264\tet al., 2025) was evaluated and compared.For downstream\n265\tevaluation, we measure automatic speech recognition performance with Whisper V3 (Radford et al., 2023) and speaker\n266\trecognition performance with Wav2Vec 2.0 (Khmelev et al.,\n267\t2025) system.\n268\t3\n269\t\n270\t\fFlow Matching-Based Speech Source Separation with Best-of-N Biometric Sampling\n271\tTable 1. Performance comparison of speech source separation\n272\tand target speaker extraction methods on the Libri2Mix test set in\n273\tterms of SI-SDR (dB), PESQ, and ESTOI. Values are reported as\n274\t“clean” / “both”.\n275\tModel\n276\tConvUnet (our)\n277\tTUnet (our)\n278\tDiffSep\n279\tSepReformer (chunk)\n280\tSepReformer (full)\n281\tMeanFlow-TSE (full)\n282\t\n283\tSI-SDR\n284\t14.42 / 9.28\n285\t17.30 / 11.25\n286\t9.60 / 11.30 / 19.22 / 13.70\n287\t17.56 / 11.68\n288\t\n289\tPESQ\n290\t2.64 / 1.65\n291\t3.11 / 1.92\n292\t2.58 / 2.45 / 3.02 / 2.14\n293\t3.27 / 2.18\n294\t\n295\tESTOI\n296\t0.90 / 0.75\n297\t0.93 / 0.79\n298\t0.78 / 0.88 / 0.92 / 0.83\n299\t0.91 / 0.80\n300\t\n301\t4.3. Evaluation Protocols and Metrics\n302\tSeparation quality is measured in terms of SI-SDR, PESQ,\n303\tand ESTOI. Downstream ASR quality is measured in terms\n304\tof cpWER and SV quality is measured in terms of EER.\n305\tFor EER evaluation, we generate verification protocols with\n306\tclean source utterances as enrollment samples and separated\n307\toutputs as test samples. For the proposed method all metrics\n308\tare computed after best-of-N selection with N = 4.\n309\t\n310\tFigure 2. Best-of-N selection on the Libri2Mix test set. Top:\n311\t“clean”; bottom: “both”. Left: cpWER (%) with Whisper V3\n312\tASR; right: EER (%) with Wav2Vec 2.0 speaker verification. Blue:\n313\tproposed biometric selection; red: SI-SDR oracle using groundtruth references.\n314\t\n315\t5. Results\n316\t\n317\tTable 2. Downstream ASR and SV performance on Libri2Mix\n318\tclean after speech separation. Metrics: cpWER (%) and EER (%).\n319\t\n320\tTable 1 reports objective separation metrics. In the “clean”\n321\tsetting, TUnet achieves the best ESTOI (0.93) and competitive SI-SDR (17.30 dB), substantially outperforming\n322\tDiffSep (9.60 dB SI-SDR). SepReformer (full) obtains the\n323\thighest SI-SDR (19.22 dB), but this configuration processes\n324\tthe full utterance at once, which makes it unsuitable for long\n325\trecordings in real-world scenarios. In the chunked setting,\n326\tSepReformer drops to 11.30 dB SI-SDR and 0.88 ESTOI.\n327\tMeanFlow-TSE achieves the best PESQ (3.27) and the best\n328\tSI-SDR/PESQ on the “both” subset, but it addresses target\n329\tspeaker extraction and uses target-speaker reference information, making it a different problem setting from blind twospeaker separation. Overall, the proposed ConvUnet and\n330\tTUnet consistently outperform DiffSep and remain competitive with state-of-the-art approaches across both conditions.\n331\t\n332\tModel\n333\tConvUnet (our)\n334\tTUnet (our)\n335\tMeanFlow-TSE (full)\n336\tSepReformer (full)\n337\tSepReformer (chunk)\n338\t\n339\tWhisper V3, cpWER\n340\t4.99\n341\t3.84\n342\t9.05\n343\t5.02\n344\t12.90\n345\t\n346\tWav2Vec 2.0, EER\n347\t0.51\n348\t0.39\n349\t2.94\n350\t0.72\n351\t1.45\n352\t\n353\tthough SepReformer (full) performs close to ConvUnet\n354\tin the full-utterance setting, its chunk-wise variant degrades substantially, which is consistent with the objective results in Table 1. An additional ablation with alternative downstream backends shows the same trend for Parakeet ASR (Sekoyan et al., 2025) and for ResNet-34 and\n355\tDistillWhisper-based (Khmelev et al., 2026) SV models,\n356\tconfirming that the observed gains are not specific to a single ASR or SV system. Overall, the downstream evaluation\n357\tshows that the proposed TUnet is the strongest option in\n358\tpractical chunk-wise processing among the evaluated systems.\n359\t\n360\tFigure 2 analyzes best-of-N sampling for the proposed\n361\tTUnet model. Additionally it compares biometric channel\n362\tselection pipeline with SI-SDR-based oracle selection using\n363\tground-truth sources. Increasing N generally reduces both\n364\tcpWER and EER for both strategies, with saturation starting\n365\taround N = 4. The biometric-based criterion, which does\n366\tnot require ground-truth references, closely approaches the\n367\toracle performance, demonstrating its practical utility for\n368\tinference-time candidate selection in generative separation.\n369\t\n370\t6. Conclusion\n371\tWe presented a novel conditional flow matching source separation approach that combines biometric source ordering,\n372\tbest-of-N candidate selection, and chunk-wise processing\n373\tfor long recordings. On Libri2Mix, the Transformer U-Net\n374\tvariant remains competitive in objective separation metrics\n375\tand achieves the best downstream cpWER and EER among\n376\tthe evaluated systems. These results indicate that the proposed system is well suited for practical speech processing\n377\tpipelines with downstream ASR and SV tasks.\n378\t\n379\tTable 2 reports downstream ASR and SV performance\n380\tafter speech separation on the Libri2Mix clean test set.\n381\tTUnet achieves the best downstream results among all evaluated systems, with 3.84% cpWER and 0.39% EER. ConvUnet also remains competitive, improving over MeanFlowTSE and SepReformer (chunk) on both metrics. Al4\n382\t\n383\t\fFlow Matching-Based Speech Source Separation with Best-of-N Biometric Sampling\n384\t\n385\tReferences\n386\t\n387\tKu, P. J. et al. Generative speech foundation model pretraining for high-quality speech extraction and restoration. In\n388\tICASSP 2025 – 2025 IEEE International Conference on\n389\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), pp.\n390\t1–5, 2025.\n391\t\n392\tAraki, S. et al. 30+ years of source separation research:\n393\tAchievements and future challenges. In ICASSP 2025\n394\t– 2025 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n395\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), pp. 1–5, 2025.\n396\tChen, M. et al. Evaluating large language models trained\n397\ton code. arXiv preprint arXiv:2107.03374, 2021.\n398\t\n399\tKuchaiev, O. et al. NeMo: A toolkit for building ai\n400\tapplications using neural modules. arXiv preprint\n401\tarXiv:1909.09577, 2019.\n402\t\n403\tChoi, C., Kim, S., and Kim, H. J. Performance plateaus in\n404\tinference-time scaling for text-to-image diffusion without\n405\texternal models. In ICML 2025 Workshop on Methods\n406\tand Opportunities at Small Scale, 2025.\n407\t\n408\tLi, K. et al. Advances in speech separation: Techniques, challenges, and future trends. arXiv preprint\n409\tarXiv:2508.10830, 2025.\n410\tLipman, Y. et al. Flow matching for generative modeling.\n411\tIn arXiv preprint arXiv:2210.02747, 2022.\n412\t\n413