{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b034e3d330df6fca", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# AISHELL-5: The First Open-Source In-Car Multi-Channel Multi-Speaker Speech Dataset for Automatic Speech Diarization and Recognition\narXiv: 2505.23036\nAuthors: Yuhang Dai, He Wang, Xingchen Li, Zihan Zhang, Shuiyuan Wang, Lei Xie, Xin Xu, Hongxiao Guo, Shaoji Zhang, Hui Bu, Wei Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AISHELL-5, the first open-source multi-channel, multi-speaker in-car Mandarin speech dataset for automatic speech diarization and recognition.\n  2. Provision of over 100 hours of real multi-channel speech data recorded across more than 60 diverse driving scenarios.\n  3. Inclusion of 40 hours of real-world environmental noise recordings to support in-car speech data simulation.\n  4. Release of an open-access, reproducible baseline system integrating speech source separation and automatic speech recognition modules.\n  5. Demonstration of the challenges of in-car speech processing by evaluating various mainstream ASR models on the dataset.\n\nTags: ASR/训练-监督, Eval/基准", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "4a4cd964-0296-4e74-b262-76d635eacb88", "uuid": "0bba7b32-8429-42e3-8d40-980b2cf532d0", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T19:51:32.585Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# AISHELL-5: The First Open-Source In-Car Multi-Channel Multi-Speaker Speech Dataset for Automatic Speech Diarization and Recognition\narXiv: 2505.23036\nAuthors: Yuhang Dai, He Wang, Xingchen Li, Zihan Zhang, Shuiyuan Wang, Lei Xie, Xin Xu, Hongxiao Guo, Shaoji Zhang, Hui Bu, Wei Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AISHELL-5, the first open-source multi-channel, multi-speaker in-car Mandarin speech dataset for automatic speech diarization and recognition.\n  2. Provision of over 100 hours of real multi-channel speech data recorded across more than 60 diverse driving scenarios.\n  3. Inclusion of 40 hours of real-world environmental noise recordings to support in-car speech data simulation.\n  4. Release of an open-access, reproducible baseline system integrating speech source separation and automatic speech recognition modules.\n  5. Demonstration of the challenges of in-car speech processing by evaluating various mainstream ASR models on the dataset.\n\nTags: ASR/训练-监督, Eval/基准", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8a355eb568c31bdf", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Contrastive Flow Matching\narXiv: 2506.05350\nAuthors: George Stoica, Vivek Ramanujan, Xiang Fan, Ali Farhadi, Ranjay Krishna, Judy Hoffman\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Contrastive Flow Matching, an extension to the flow matching objective that explicitly enforces uniqueness across conditional flows to enhance condition separation.\n  2. Adds a contrastive regularization term that maximizes dissimilarities between predicted flows from arbitrary sample pairs within a training batch.\n  3. Demonstrates up to 9x faster training speed compared to standard flow matching.\n  4. Achieves equivalent or superior image quality with up to 5x fewer denoising steps during inference.\n  5. Lowers Fréchet Inception Distance (FID) by up to 8.9 points on class-conditional and text-to-image benchmarks.\n  6. Shows complementary benefits when combined with Representation Alignment (REPA) for further performance improvements.\n  7. Introduces a modified classifier-free guidance equation to resolve conflicts and successfully stack the benefits of both methods.", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "4a4cd964-0296-4e74-b262-76d635eacb88", "uuid": "3461acb3-0824-4a71-bb4a-39e0253919fa", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T19:51:32.808Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Contrastive Flow Matching\narXiv: 2506.05350\nAuthors: George Stoica, Vivek Ramanujan, Xiang Fan, Ali Farhadi, Ranjay Krishna, Judy Hoffman\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Contrastive Flow Matching, an extension to the flow matching objective that explicitly enforces uniqueness across conditional flows to enhance condition separation.\n  2. Adds a contrastive regularization term that maximizes dissimilarities between predicted flows from arbitrary sample pairs within a training batch.\n  3. Demonstrates up to 9x faster training speed compared to standard flow matching.\n  4. Achieves equivalent or superior image quality with up to 5x fewer denoising steps during inference.\n  5. Lowers Fréchet Inception Distance (FID) by up to 8.9 points on class-conditional and text-to-image benchmarks.\n  6. Shows complementary benefits when combined with Representation Alignment (REPA) for further performance improvements.\n  7. Introduces a modified classifier-free guidance equation to resolve conflicts and successfully stack the benefits of both methods.", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
